dence, cross examined by Solicitor General. Case heard by Lord Chief Justice Goddard. Notorious for heavy sentences but took pity on two young Oxford undergraduates. Gave them a backdated sentence of three months. Only served one month. He instructed the 
Prison Commissioners to be gentle. Went to an ordinary prison for just a few hours \endash  a bit of rough handling, quite frightening \endash 
 then to an open prison. Soon realised the prison was run by the professional prisoners. If you got involved in the tobacco racket and did the wrong thing you\rquote d be beaten up. Didn\rquote t take his own tobacco \endash 
 avoided that. William was very good at handling people. Would have sunk on his own. Very illuminating. Met a lot of working class people in a way he hadn\rquote t before. There with a gr
oup of porters from Covent Garden, used to greet him when he walked through. A lot of people thought it would end his career. Backed, however, by mediaevalist tutor. Peter Townsend at Essex thought it was a very important, positive experience. Lucky!}{
